Conjugated polymerized bimetallic phthalocyanine based electrocatalyst with Fe−N4/Co−N4 dual-sites synergistic effect for zinc-air battery Shuaifeng Wang Zhongfang Li ⁎ Wenjie Duan Peng Sun Jigang Wang Qiang Liu Lei Zhang Yanqiong Zhuang School of Chemistry and Chemical Engineering, Shandong University of Technology, Zibo 255049, Shandong, China School of Chemistry and Chemical Engineering Shandong University of Technology Zibo Shandong 255049 China School of Chemistry and Chemical Engineering, Shandong University of Technology, Zibo 255049, Shandong, China ⁎ Corresponding author. Graphical abstract PPcFeCo/3D-G, with dual-site (FeN4 and CoN4) synergistic effect, is an excellent bifunctional cathode electrocatalyst, which has excellent half-wave potential (0.890 V vs. RHE) and small overvoltage (0.700 V). The bifunctional oxygen catalyst is essential for zinc-air batteries (ZABs). Here, an efficient bifunctional oxygen catalyst, PPcFeCo/3D-G, is obtained through π-π interaction between the conjugated polymerized iron-cobalt phthalocyanine (PPcFeCo) with excellent thermal stability and three-dimensional graphene (3D-G). The bimetallic synergistic effect of PPcFeCo, verified by DFT (Density functional theory) calculation, and π-π interactions enhances the catalytic activity and durability of the PPcFeCo/3D-G. Regarding electrochemical performance, the PPcFeCo/3D-G with a high electron transfer number (3.98, @0.768 V vs. RHE) has excellent half-wave potential (E 1/2 = 0.890 V vs. RHE) and exhibits outstanding reversibility (ΔE = 0.700 V, ΔE = E j=10 − E 1/2). The liquid ZAB (LZAB) employed PPcFeCo/3D-G displays a high power density (222 mW cm−2), a specific capacity (792 mA h g−1), and excellent durability (120 h). This work has guiding significance for the preparation of high-efficiency bifunctional catalysts. Keywords Zn-air battery Bifunctional oxygen catalysts Polymerized iron-cobalt phthalocyanine Bimetallic synergy π-π interaction 1 Introduction In the context of the energy crisis and environmental pollution problems, it is paramount to develop sustainable energy alternatives to traditional fossil fuels [1–3]. Zinc air batteries (ZABs) have great potential for development because of their high working efficiency and pollution-free environment [4,5]. The performance of the ZAB is influenced by the two significant half-reactions, oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) and oxygen evolution reaction (OER) [6–8]. However, the sluggish kinetics of ORR and OER is the bottleneck of performance improvement and commercial development for ZAB [9,10]. Moreover, precious metal catalysts, such as Pt, Ir, and Ru catalysts, are the mainstream catalysts, but the scarcity, high cost, and single function make ZAB difficult to achieve promotion [11–13]. Thus, it is necessary to develop a low-cost and highly efficient bifunctional non-noble metal oxygen electrocatalyst for ZAB. In the past decade, transition metal and heteroatom-doped carbon-based catalysts have been investigated extensively due to their low cost and wide availability of raw materials [14–16]. However, the preparation of such catalysts requires high-temperature pyrolysis, which suffers from low atomic utilization, transition metal clustering, and uncontrolled active site structure [17–19]. In recent years, single-atom catalysts (SACs) have become the focus of research because of their excellent catalytic performance, high atomic utilization, and well-defined site structure. Nitrogen in nitrogen-doped carbon (N-C) materials has lone pair electrons that can anchor metal atoms, which is usually used to construct SACs [20–23]. However, these SACs also exhibit some drawbacks [24–26]: (1) The low doping level of metal atoms leads to a low density of active sites, and the active sites are easily occupied by intermediates causing catalyst deactivation; (2) The structural stability is poor due to the cluster-prone metal atoms and the weak interaction between the M−N x site and the carrier; (3) A single active center fails to conduct electron transfer efficiently. To solve these problems, it is significant to propose stronger atomic anchoring strategies to improve the loading of metal atoms with the structural stability of the catalysts. Other metal atoms were introduced to change the electronic effect of the central metal and construct heteronuclear diatomic catalysts (HDMCs). Since Jasinski first published its report in 1964, metal phthalocyanine (PcM) has become an ideal electrocatalytic material due to its highly modifiable processability and potential ORR and OER activities [27]. With the intensive research on phthalocyanine, its applications are becoming more and more widespread, including electrocatalytic reduction of carbon dioxide [28,29], electrocatalytic production of hydrogen peroxide[30], electrolytic water [31,32], supercapacitors [33,34], and batteries [35–39]. Especially, the formation of a strong metal nitrogen (M−N) bond between the phthalocyanine (Pc) ring and a transition metal atom can firmly anchor a transition metal atom. In addition, the clear M−N4 structure of PcM is conducive to the study of the catalytic mechanisms [40,41]. However, due to the inherent semiconductor properties of Pc molecules, the electron transfer during electrocatalysis is limited, thus affecting its electrochemical performance. Currently, electrocatalysts based on PcM are predominantly obtained by direct pyrolysis of PcM or composite with a conductive carrier [42]. However, phthalocyanine is decomposed into metal nitrogen carbon clusters by conventional pyrolysis process [43–45]. When PcM is combined with conductive materials such as graphene and carbon nanotubes to form composite materials, it tends to stack on the surface of the conductive materials, resulting in reduced utilization [41]. Therefore, it is vital to conduct additional research into the impact of molecular structure on the physical and chemical properties of phthalocyanine molecules, the influence of support on the performance of phthalocyanine catalysts, and to develop non-pyrolysis or controllable pyrolysis strategies. Based on the flexible design processability of phthalocyanine molecules, polymerization to enhance their thermal and spatial structural stability is one of the most effective methods [46–50]. The extended π-electron conjugated polymerization system is obtained by connecting PcM molecules with a benzene ring, which has excellent stability and catalytic performance. In addition, the introduction of two different transition metal atoms into the polymeric phthalocyanine system changes the original electronic effect of the metal and reduces the adsorption energy of oxygen. The 3D-G effectively prevents the problems of agglomeration of CNT and stacking of 2D-G and retains the excellent properties of graphene [51]. Herein, the conjugated polymerization system (PPFeCo) (Fig. S1) with larger π-electron delocalization energy reduces the energy of the system, which improves thermal stability. The energy gap of PPcFeCo between the highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) and the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) improves the ability to gain or lose electrons. Especially, the synergistic effect of the Fe-N4/Co-N4 double site reduces the oxygen adsorption energy and accelerates the kinetic process of the ORR and OER. The 3D-G with a large specific surface area, multiple through pore structure, and outstanding conductivity was obtained by high-temperature pyrolysis process with coal tar pitch as the carbon source, and MgO/ZnO as the mixed template. In particular, PPcFeCo is firmly adsorbed on the 3D-G surface through the π-π interaction between it and 3D-G, enhancing the catalytic performance and durability of PPcFeCo/3D-G. The synthetic strategy of PPcFeCo/3D-G is shown in Scheme 1 . 2 Experimental 2.1 Material synthesis The sources of the chemicals and reagents used in the experiments are shown in S1 in the Supporting information. Based on a previously published work, the solid-state technique was used to synthesize the PPcFeCo with a few minor alterations [40]. Pyromellitic dianhydride, ammonium molybdate, ammonium ferrous sulfate, cobalt chloride, and urea were placed in a sealed pressure vessel and heated to obtain the initial product of PPcFeCo. The initial product was placed in the crucible and heated to get the crude product. The crude product was purified to get PPcFeCo. Using coal bitumen as the carbon source, and MgO/ZnO as the templates, 3D-G was obtained by removing the templates after pyrolysis under nitrogen protection. The PPcFeCo/3D-G was prepared by the method of intensive impregnation. Specific experimental procedures are described in detail in S2 in the Supporting information. 2.2 Characterization and electrochemical method 2.2.1 Characterization method The prepared materials were qualitatively analyzed by Ultraviolet–Visible spectra (UV–Vis) and UV–Vis diffuse reflectance absorption spectra (UV–Vis-DRS). A Nicolet 5700 transmission spectrophotometer was used to characterize the FT-IR spectra using the KBr pellet technique. Thermogravimetric (TG) analysis, carried out using STA-409 Netsch under a nitrogen environment with a flow rate of 30.0 mL min−1 and a heating rate of 10 °C min−1, was used to investigate the material's thermal stability. The 1H nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) and 13C solid-state nuclear magnetic were measured on Bruker ADVANCE III 400. On a PHI-5300 ESCA spectrometer, the XPS (Perkin Elmer Instruments, Waltham, MA) analyzes the elemental makeup and valence states of the materials. The micromorphology of the samples was observed with SEM (FEI Sirion 200) and TEM (JEOL 2100). The XRD (D8 Advance, Bruker, German) was used to characterize the crystal structure of the samples with Cu-K α radiation (λ = 1.54178 Å) at a speed of 6° min−1. A Raman spectrometer (HORIBA, Japan) with a wavelength of 532 nm was used to record the Raman spectra. Micromeritics ASAP 2020 instrument was employed to analyze the sample's BET area and pore size distribution. The inductively coupled plasma mass spectroscopy (ICP-MS) analysis was performed on an Agilent 7500ce (Agilent Technologies, Tokyo, Japan). 2.2.2 Electrochemical measurement The electrocatalytic properties of catalysts were assessed on a CHI760E electrochemical workstation with a three-electrode cell. Here, the rotating disk electrode (RDE, diameter: 5 mm) and a rotating-ring disk electrode (RRDE, diameter: 5.61 mm) were used as the working electrode, and the graphite rod was employed as the counter electrode, and the Ag/AgCl (0.966 V vs. RHE) electrode was used as the reference electrode, respectively. ORR performance was tested in 0.1 M KOH solution and OER performance was tested in 1 M KOH solution. Further details of the catalytic performance tests are described in the S3. 2.2.3 Zinc-air batteries measurement The performance of LZAB and flexible ZAB (FZAB) was measured to assess the practical application value of the catalyst. The galvanostatic discharge curves, the power density plots, and the discharge polarization were all evaluated using the electronic load instrument (M9700, Maynuo Company, Nanjing, China). The galvanic charge–discharge curves of the ZAB were tested using the NEWARE system (CT-1008-5V6A-S1-F, neware). The S4 (Supporting information) includes a detailed description of the LZAB and FZAB assembly procedures. 2.3 Computational details The first-principles calculations are performed using the framework of density functional theory (DFT) within the Vienna ab initio simulation package (VASP) [52,53]. The exchange–correlation interaction was processed using a generalized gradient approximation (GGA) in the form of Perdew-Burke-Ernzerhof (PBE) [54]. The thickness of the vacuum layer in the Z-direction was fixed at 20 Å using IOPTCELL to avoid the effect of interactions between adjacent fragments. Unit cell sizes of 10.6 Å × 10.6 Å × 20 Å, 10.6 Å × 10.6 Å × 20 Å, and 21.1 Å × 10.6 Å × 20 Å were used to simulate PPcFe, PPcCo, and PPcFeCo, respectively. The kinetic energy cutoff of the plane wave used to extend the Kohn-Sham electron wave function was set to 400 eV. The iterative convergence of energy is 10−5 eV. All atoms were allowed to relax until the Hellmann-Feynman force was less than 0.01 eV Å−1. The Brillouin zone was sampled by a 1 × 1 × 1 k-point grid for PPcFe and PPcCo. The Brillouin zone was sampled by a 1 × 2 × 1 k-point grid for PPcFeCo. Further details of the DFT calculation are described in the S5 (in the Supporting information). The charge density difference (Fig. S6) is used to study the π-π interaction between PPcFeCo and 3D-G, defined as Δρ = ρ (A/B) − ρ A − ρ B. Where Δρ is the charge density difference, ρ (A/B) is the total electron density of the PPcFeCo/3D-G. ρ A and ρ B are the total electron densities of isolated PPcFeCo and 3D-G, respectively. 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Characterization of PPcFeCo and PPcFeCo/3D-G UV–Vis absorption spectroscopy was used to perform the qualitative investigation of metal phthalocyanines. The PPcFeCo generally exhibits two distinctive peaks in its UV–Vis absorption spectrum, belonging to the B band (260–350 nm) and the Q band (600–700 nm) [55]]. All the phthalocyanine samples have B-band and Q-band absorption peaks, shown in Fig. 1 (a), indicating the successful synthesis of phthalocyanine. Especially, the B and Q bands of polymeric metal phthalocyanines (PPcFeCo, PPcFe, and PPcCo) are red-shifted concerning the B and Q bands of monomeric phthalocyanines (PcFe and PcCo), which were caused by the increased conjugation effect after polymerization. It demonstrates the successful synthesis of polymeric metal phthalocyanines. The structure of the PPcFeCo was further confirmed by 13C solid-state nuclear magnetic, 1H NMR ((CD3)2SO, ppm), and FT-IR. The 13C solid-state nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectra (Fig. 1b) of PPcFeCo showed four peaks: δ 171.2, δ 168.9, δ 138.7, δ 118.7. The peaks located at δ 171.2 and δ 168.9 belong to the carbons (a and b) of the phthalocyanine ring, respectively, and the ones located at δ 138.7 and δ 118.7 belong to the carbons (c and d) in the aromatic ring [56]. As shown in Fig. S2(a), the 1H NMR of PPcFeCo (400 MHz, (CD3)2SO, ppm): δ 11.87, δ 8.3, δ 8.1, δ 7.2, δ 7.07, and δ 6.94. The peak located at δ 11.87 is corresponding to the proton in the amide groups. The peaks located at δ 8.3, δ 8.1, δ 7.2, δ 7.07, and δ 6.94 belongs to the proton of the phthalocyanine rings. The FT-IR spectrum is shown in Fig. S2(b), which is consistent with the above results [57]. According to the TG curves in Fig. 1(c), the mass loss of PPcFeCo at 400 °C is negligible, whereas the loss of PcFe (5.0%) and PcCo (7.0%) is greater, indicating the excellent thermal stability of PPcFeCo due to the stable structure. The PPcFeCo system containing delocalized π-bonds has a large electron delocalization energy, making the system more thermally stable with reduced energy. The UV–Vis diffuse reflectance absorption spectra of PPcFeCo/3D-G and PPcFeCo, displayed in Fig. 1(d), show a red-shift. This is due to the π-π interaction between PPcFeCo and 3D-G [57]. The π-π interaction will make PPcFeCo/3D-G have excellent catalyzed ORR performance and durability. Additionally, it suggests that the Fe and Co atoms in PPcFeCo exist as FeN4 and CoN4, respectively. Besides, Fig. S3(c and d) shows the presence of OC (531.3 eV) which in combination with the above analysis can indicate the presence of amide groups. The C 1s peak, shown in Fig. 2(d), was divided into four peaks: 288.36, 285.2, 284.8, and 284.5 eV, which correspond to CN, CN, CC, and CC, respectively [58]. Those results further demonstrate that, as illustrated in Fig. S1, the PPcFeCo has a conjugated planar structure. Those indicate that the heat treatment did not affect the original form of the Fe and Co elements. It only reduced the content of CONH2. Especially, the binding energies of Fe, Co, and N elements are reduced after PPcFeCo is compounded with 3D-G, which is due to the increase in the outer electron density of Fe, Co, and N atoms due to π-π interaction (Fig. S6), which leads to an increase in the shielding effect and consequently a decrease in the binding energy. The optimum preparation process (Fig. S8a and b) of PPcFeCo/3D-G is that the mass ratio of PPcFeCo to 3D-G is 1:1 and the activation temperature of the catalyst is 400 °C. The detailed data on the catalytic performance of the catalysts prepared in this work are listed in Table S2. It indicated that PPcFeCo/3D-G has excellent catalytic performance compared with other catalysts. The specific analysis and discussion are as follows. By using the CV method, the electrocatalytic activity of the produced catalysts was investigated. The CV curves which exhibit significant oxygen reduction peaks of the prepared samples, shown in Fig. 5 (a) indicate that the catalysts have oxygen reduction catalytic performance. In comparison to PPcFe/3D-G, PPcCo/3D-G, and 20 wt% Pt/C, PPcFeCo/3D-G shows a noticeable oxygen-reducing activity, suggesting it has the best catalytic activity. Based on K-L plots, the electron transfer number of PPcFeCo/3D-G is calculated and shown in Fig. S9. Furthermore, the result of RRDE, as shown in Fig. 5(d), showed that the yield of hydrogen peroxide in the catalytic reaction of PPcFeCo/3D-G was very small, indicating PPcFeCo/3D-G has excellent selectivity. The PPcFeCo/3D-G have favorable ORR kinetics with a small Tafel slope (55 mV dec−1), as shown in Fig. 5(e), which is superior to PPcFe/3D-G (75 mV dec−1), PPcCo/3D-G (57 mV dec−1), PPcFe&PPcCo/3D-G (75 mV dec−1) and 20 wt% Pt/C (80 mV dec−1). Remarkably, TG, UV–vis-DRS, XRD, SAED, and XPS revealed that PPcFeCo is still well preserved after heat treatment (400 °C). The geometric structure models of PPcFe, PPcCo, and PPcFeCo (FeN4 site and CoN4 site) along with their adsorption intermediates (OOH, O, OH) are shown in Fig. 6 (a–d). The ΔG of the OER is 4.92 eV and the ΔG at each electron step in the four-electron process is 1.23 eV in the ideal case. However, in practical terms, the potential required for OER to occur is greater than 1.23 eV, and the excess of 1.23 eV is the overpotential. In the four-electron process of OER, the adsorption energy of the catalyst's active site to the intermediate determines the catalytic activity of the catalyst. As shown in Fig. 6(e and f), the minimum potential required to generate OER at the FeN4 site of PPcFe is 2.3 eV and the overpotential is 1.07 eV. The minimum potential required to generate OER at the CoN4 site of PPcCo is 1.74 eV and the overpotential is 0.51 eV. As shown in Fig. 6(g and h), the minimum potentials required to generate OER at the CoN4 and FeN4 sites of PPcFeCo are 1.76 eV and 1.61 eV, with the overpotentials 0.53 eV and 0.38 eV, respectively. As shown above, PPcFeCo (FeN4) has the smallest overpotential (0.38 eV) compared to PPcFe and PPcCo, which indicates that PPcFeCo has a higher OER catalytic activity. This is consistent with the experimental results in Fig. 5(j). The adsorption energy of the catalyst active site on the intermediate was further analyzed to investigate the synergistic mechanism of FeN4 and CoN4. The adsorption energies of the catalyst active sites for oxygen molecules and intermediates are shown in Fig. 6(i). The adsorption energy of PPcFe for both oxygen molecules and intermediates is greater than that of other catalysts for oxygen molecules and intermediates, i.e. PPcFe has a strong adsorption effect. However, PPcCo exhibited weaker adsorption. In addition, PPcFe and PPcCo have a large overpotential. The adsorption energy of PPcFeCo (FeN4) for both oxygen molecules and intermediates is between PPcFe and PPcCo, which indicates that the strength of PPcFeCo (FeN4) adsorption substrate is also between PPcFe and PPcCo, and PPcFeCo (FeN4) has the smallest overpotential. The relationship curve (Fig. 6j) between catalytic activity and the adsorption energy of the catalyst shows that the adsorption energy of the catalyst on the substrate determines the catalytic activity of the catalyst, and high or low adsorption energy will result in low catalytic activity. Surprisingly, The FeN4/CoN4 synergy in PPcFeCo changes the original d-orbital energy levels of the Fe and Co atoms in PPcFe and PPcCo, resulting in a change in their adsorption energy to the substrate. The change in the d-orbital energy levels of Fe and Co allows PPcFeCo to have a suitable adsorption strength to the substrate, which results in a minimum overpotential for PPcFeCo. This also explains the superior catalytic activity of PPcFeCo/3D-G compared to PPcFe/3D-G, PPcCo/3D-G, and PPcFe&PPcCo/3D-G. 3.4 Application in LZAB and FZAB The prepared PPcFeCo/3D-G was applied to the cathode catalyst of ZAB to verify its excellent dual-function performance. The discharge polarization curve of LZAB was obtained by using an electronic load test and further processed to obtain the peak power density curve. The PPcFeCo/3D-G display an open-circuit voltage and the peak power density, shown in Fig. 7(b), as high as 1.350 V and 222 mW cm−2, superior to those of PPcFe/3D-G (∼1.290 V, 195 mW cm−2), PPcCo/3D-G (∼1.340 V, 161 mW cm−2), PPcFe&PPcCo/3D-G (∼1.290 V, 183 mW cm−2), and 20 wt% Pt/C + RuO2 (∼1.210 V, 174 mW cm−2). The LZAB with PPcFeCo/3D-G (Fig. 7c) displays the specific capacity of 792 mA h g−1, superior to the PPcFe/3D-G (762 mA h g−1), PPcCo/3D-G (753 mA h g−1), PPcFe&PPcCo/3D-G (781 mA h g−1) and 20 wt% Pt/C + RuO2 (540 mA h g−1). The charge/discharge (D-C) polarization curves of LZABs are shown in Fig. 7(d), with PPcFeCo/3D-G, PPcFe/3D-G, PPcCo/3D-G, PPcFe&PPcCo/3D-G, and 20 wt% Pt/C + RuO2 as cathode catalysts, respectively. In comparison to PPcFe/3D-G (1.180 V), PPcCo/3D-G (1.170 V), PPcFe&PPcCo/3D-G (1.270 V), and 20 wt% Pt/C + RuO2 (1.200 V), the D-C voltage gap of the LZAB with PPcFeCo/3D-G is 1.030 V at 100 mA cm−2. According to these results, the PPcFeCo/3D-G catalyst has a higher activity than the catalysts mentioned above, which is compatible with the outcomes of the ORR tests. The charge/discharge plateau of the LZAB with PPcFeCo/3D-G has not significantly changed after 720 cycles (over 120 h), as shown in Fig. 7(e), while the LZAB with 20 wt% Pt/C + RuO2 has higher charging voltages and lower discharging voltages after 150 cycles (more than 25 h). As shown in Fig. S11, the cycle charge/discharge durability of the LZAB with PPcFeCo/3D-G as cathode catalysis at current densities of 5 and 15 mA cm−2, indicates that the LZAB exhibits excellent durability. According to the results of the aforementioned experiment, PPcFeCo/3D-G is an excellent bifunctional catalyst. The electrode process of LZAB was further analyzed using electrochemical impedance spectroscopy. Fig. 7(f) shows that the impedance spectra consist of a semicircle in the high-frequency region and a straight line in the low-frequency region, where the high-frequency region is controlled by the kinetics of the electrode reaction and the low-frequency region is controlled by the diffusion of the reactants or products of the electrode reaction, indicating that the electrode process of LZAB is controlled by charge transfer and diffusion processes. The solution resistance (R Ω) of LZAB with PPcFeCo/3D-G as the cathode catalyst was 5.0 Ω and the interfacial transfer resistance (R ct) was 35.0 Ω which was smaller than that of LZAB with PPcFe&PPcCo/3D-G as the cathode catalysts (R Ω = 8.0 Ω and R ct = 39.0 Ω). This indicates that LZAB with PPcFeCo/3D-G as the cathode catalyst has a higher charge transfer rate and faster mass diffusion process [64]. The catalyst was also applied to FZAB (Fig. 7g). The FZAB with PPcFeCo/3D-G, as shown in Fig. 7(h), shows an excellent peak power density (59 mW cm−2) which is better than that of 20 wt% Pt/C + RuO2 (46 mW cm−2), and shows a smaller C-D potential gap than that of 20 wt% Pt/C + RuO2. The FZAB with PPcFeCo/3D-G has a long constant-current discharge of 11 h, as shown in Fig. 7(i), better than FZAB with 20 wt% Pt/C + RuO2 (9.8 h). The charge/discharge durability tests (Fig. 7j) indicate that the FZAB with PPcFeCo/3D-G has excellent durability. It's noteworthy that Fig. 7(k) shows that the FZAB with PPcFeCo/3D-G still works properly when it is bent by external forces. The above results indicate that PPcFeCo/3D-G has practical application significance. 4 Conclusions PPcFeCo, with a large conjugated structure, was successfully synthesized by the solid-state method. The 3D-G was prepared by the mixed template method (MgO and ZnO). The excellent durability of PPcFeCo/3D-G is attributed to the excellent thermal stability of PPcFeCo and π-π interaction. In addition, PPcFeCo/3D-G has a well-defined structure of active sites (FeN4 and CoN4). Moreover, the results of the DFT calculation are consistent with the experimental results, which verifies the synergistic effect between FeN4 and CoN4, making a great contribution to the improvement of catalyst performance. Especially, the synergistic effect of FeN4/CoN4 double sites changes the original d-orbital energy levels of iron and cobalt atoms, making PPcFeCo have appropriate adsorption strength to the substrate, thus PPcFeCo/3D-G have excellent catalytic activity. The E 1/2 of PPcFeCo/3D-G is 0.890 V vs. RHE in alkaline conditions, which is higher than that of PcFe/3D-G, PPcCo/3D-G, PPcFe&PPcCo/3D-G, 20 wt% Pt/C, and most metal phthalocyanines reported recently. The overvoltage of PPcFeCo/3D-G is smaller than that of the above catalysts. Furthermore, the LZAB and FZAB with PPcFeCo/3D-G as a cathode catalyst display excellent performance (power density: 222 mW cm−2). This work provides a simple method for constructing HDMCs. coredata.dc:description: The bifunctional oxygen catalyst is essential for zinc-air batteries (ZABs). Here, an efficient bifunctional oxygen catalyst, PPcFeCo/3D-G, is obtained through π-π interaction between the conjugated polymerized iron-cobalt phthalocyanine (PPcFeCo) with excellent thermal stability and three-dimensional graphene (3D-G). The bimetallic synergistic effect of PPcFeCo, verified by DFT (Density functional theory) calculation, and π-π interactions enhances the catalytic activity and durability of the PPcFeCo/3D-G. Regarding electrochemical performance, the PPcFeCo/3D-G with a high electron transfer number (3.98, @0.768 V vs. RHE) has excellent half-wave potential (E 1/2 = 0.890 V vs. RHE) and exhibits outstanding reversibility (ΔE = 0.700 V, ΔE = E j=10 − E 1/2). The liquid ZAB (LZAB) employed PPcFeCo/3D-G displays a high power density (222 mW cm−2), a specific capacity (792 mA h g−1), and excellent durability (120 h). This work has guiding significance for the preparation of high-efficiency bifunctional catalysts.
